  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (from activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and other crimes) appear legal by disguising their true origin. This practice is universally condemned and is criminalized in most jurisdictions around the world.\n\nInternational organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have developed comprehensive frameworks and guidelines to combat money laundering. National governments have enacted laws and regulations that criminalize money laundering and impose severe penalties, including substantial fines and imprisonment, for those who engage in such activities.\n\nEfforts to combat money laundering are also supported by financial institutions, which are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures, conduct due diligence on their customers, and report suspicious activities to relevant authorities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely recognized as a criminal activity, and there is a global consensus on the need to prevent, detect, and prosecute it.",
